      "title": "Module 1: The envy reflex, reframed",
      "text": "When you see someone smoking and feel a flicker of \"I wish I could,\" understand exactly what that is. It's an old association firing, plus a leftover scrap of the belief that they're getting something you're not. Look closer and the picture flips. That person isn't enjoying a treat you're denied. They're feeding an addiction you've escaped. They'll smoke that one, get a few minutes of partial relief, and then the monster will start nagging them again within the hour — all day, every day, for as long as they stay trapped. They're standing in the cold, paying for the privilege, planning their day around the next one.\n\nSo the accurate emotion isn't envy — it's relief, and maybe a little compassion. Reappraisal is a core CBT skill: same scene, truer interpretation, different feeling. Practise seeing the smoker as someone still inside the maze you just walked out of. You wouldn't envy someone still serving a sentence you've been released from."
