      "title": "Module 2: Handling the offer",
      "text": "Someone will offer you a cigarette, or you'll be in a group where everyone lights up. You need a response that's ready, clean, and final — no internal debate required. The strongest answer is simple and proud: \"No thanks, I don't smoke.\" Notice the wording. Not \"I'm trying to quit,\" not \"I've given up\" — those frame you as a smoker currently deprived, and they invite negotiation (\"go on, just one\"). \"I don't smoke\" states an identity, closes the topic, and needs no defending. Say it warmly and move on.\n\nIf pressed, you don't owe anyone an explanation or a debate. A friendly, settled \"I'm good, honestly\" is plenty. And here's a quiet bonus: when other smokers see that your freedom genuinely isn't bothering you, it unsettles them in a useful way — some of them are halfway to wanting out themselves, and your ease plants a seed."
